message.content:
A Solanum dulcamara is a species of flowering vine in the nightshade family.
It typically grows up to 2-3 meters in length, with a thin stem that is green in color.
The leaves are alternate, dark green, and often lobed, with a slightly shiny texture.
It produces small flowers with five petals that are typically purple in color and bloom in the summer.
Following the flowers, it produces small, spherical berries that are green when immature and red when ripe.
Solanum dulcamara is commonly found in wetland areas, along stream banks, and in disturbed areas.
It has been used in traditional medicine to treat a variety of ailments, but its toxins make it potentially dangerous if ingested in large quantities.
